2026-04-16 12:18:43 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor module: light‑sensor / comparator / relay‑drive circuitry (upstream of relay contacts)'] hypothesis_explanation='12 V with correct polarity is present at the ambient sensor module input, and the power‑supply LED confirms the source is good. However, the ambient sensor module output that feeds the load module sits around 0.36 V / 0 V and does not change when the lamp is expected to turn on or off. The same low, constant voltage is seen at the load module input and at the series diode anode, so the load module (diode and lamps) never receives anywhere near 12 V. This proves that the fault lies upstream, inside the ambient sensor module.\n\nThe relay itself is not switching the 12 V through to its output, and the measured 0.36 V is characteristic of a weak leakage or partially biased semiconductor path rather than a properly closed relay contact. Since adjusting the timing and sensitivity potentiometers across their full range has no effect on the output, the problem is not simply a mis‑adjusted threshold. The most likely root cause is a failure in the light‑sensor/comparator/driver electronics that energize the relay coil (or the coil drive path itself), preventing the relay from ever closing fully and leaving only a small leakage voltage at the output.\n\nThus, the suspected faulty components are within the ambient sensor module, specifically the light‑sensor and comparator / relay‑drive circuitry upstream of the relay contacts. Repair or replacement of this module (or its sensor/driver subassembly) should restore proper switching of 12 V to the load module.'
