2026-04-16 12:19:25 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor module: Control Output Cable (−) terminal connection / wiring between module 0 V rail and Control Output Cable (−)', 'ambient sensor module: internal 0 V reference connection between relay / sensor circuitry and the module’s output 0 V terminal'] hypothesis_explanation='The control‑module relay input sees the full 12 V relative to the module’s internal 0 V, confirming that the upstream sensor, comparator, and relay‑drive circuits are fine and that 12 V is available at the relay. However, only ~0.36 V appears between the Control Output Cable (+) and Control Output Cable (−), and this same small voltage is seen at the load module inputs and at the diode anode. That means the full 12 V present at the relay input is being dropped somewhere within the control module between the relay/0 V reference and the two output cables. We have already ruled out an open or bad connection between the relay’s switched contact and the Output (+) terminal. The only remaining way to see only ~0.36 V across the two output cables—while one side of the relay still sits at 12 V—is if the output 0 V reference is not actually connected to the module’s internal 0 V rail. In that case, the Output (+) line is being pulled up only slightly above the floating Output (−) line through leakage or high‑impedance paths, yielding the observed ~0.36 V but no real current capability.\n\nThus the fault must be in the 0 V side of the control module’s output: a broken PCB trace, cold solder joint, or faulty/crimped connection at the Control Output Cable (−) terminal, or an internal mis‑wiring that leaves the output 0 V terminal disconnected from the module’s 0 V rail. Repairing/re‑making the wiring/trace from the ambient sensor module’s internal 0 V node to the Control Output Cable (−) terminal should restore a solid 0 V reference and allow the relay to deliver the full 12 V across the load when closed.'
