2026-04-16 12:19:52 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor module: switched‑cables indicator LED branch (LED and its series resistor, wiring/PCB connection)'] hypothesis_explanation='All measurements show 12 V present at the relay input but only ~0.36 V reaching the control‑output cables and then the load module, with essentially 0 V across the lamps. The power‑supply module and inter‑module cabling (including polarity) are verified good. The relay input sees 12 V, and multiple earlier hypotheses about the relay drive, relay contacts, and output‑terminal connections have been ruled out by repair attempts.\n\nThe remaining element in the control path that can consistently clamp the relay output node to a small non‑zero voltage (~0.36 V) is the indicator LED branch that monitors the switched cables. If this LED/resistor branch (or its wiring/PCB connection) is shorted or otherwise incorrectly connected between the relay output node and 0 V, it will load the node heavily and prevent the full 12 V from appearing on the Control Output Cable (+). The resulting small leakage voltage (~0.3–0.4 V) is exactly what is being observed at the control‑output and load‑input terminals, and explains why the lamp never truly receives supply voltage even though the relay is energized and the rest of the wiring is correct.\n\nThus the most plausible single fault is a shorted or mis‑soldered switched‑cables indicator LED branch inside the ambient sensor module that is pulling the relay’s switched contact toward ground and limiting the output to ~0.36 V.'
